result.execSummary:
The defendant Melissa R Johnson was found guilty of the following charge(s) in this case.

  • Possession of Narcotic Drugs, a class I felony, Wisconsin Statutes 961.41(3g)(am).

Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

records.addlTxt: Attorney Darryl Everett Smith in court.  Katherine Seelow appeared for the State of Wisconsin.  Defense counsel advised the Court the defendant is deceased, which was verified by the Medical Examiner's office through ADA Seelow.  No further action taken.

Sentencing Proceeded. Statements by parties and defendant.

AS TO COUNT 1:

The Court sentenced the defendant to a MAXIMUM TERM OF IMPRISONMENT of 3 1/2 YEARS, with credit for 51 days time served; the INITIAL TERM OF CONFINEMENT in the Wisconsin State Prison System is 1 1/2  YEARS; the MAXIMUM TERM OF EXTENDED SUPERVISION is 2 YEARS.  

Defendant is NOT eligible for the Challenge Incarceration Program or the Substance Abuse Program. 

Court STAYED sentence and placed defendant on PROBATION for 3 years.

-Serve 120 days  in the House of Correction as Condition Time, STAYED pending review on 05-25-2017 at 8:30 am.
-AODA assessment, comply with recommended treatment.
-Absolute sobriety, random urine screens.
-Obtain/maintain employment.
-No contact with firearms.
-Pay all MANDATORY court costs, fees, and surcharges including: DNA surcharges during period of probation, failure to pay will result in a civil judgment. 
-Court WAIVED all other court costs, fees, and surcharges due to inability to pay.
-Provide DNA Sample.
